<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910122-0022</DOCNO><DOCID>910122-0022.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- General Public Utilities Corp.:   Capital Investment Estimate   For Legal Compliance Cut</HL><DATE>01/22/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C16</SO><CO>   GPU</CO><IN>ELECTRIC UTILITIES (ELC)</IN><LP>   General Public Utilities Corp., an electric utilityholding company based in Parsippany, N.J., said it loweredits estimate of capital investment needed to comply withpower-plant emission laws to $675 million from $1 billionthrough 2000.   The company further estimated that by 2001, after thesechanges are completed, the cost of such compliance tocustomers will be $203 million annually. It serves more than1.8 million customers in Pennsylvania and New Jersey. Inaddition, rate increases will be needed at General PublicUtilities' three operating units: 6.2% for PennsylvaniaElectric Co., 4.1% for Metropolitan Edison Co. and 1% forJersey Central Power andamp; Light Co.</LP><TEXT>   Standley H. Hoch, chairman, president and chief executiveofficer, said the revised estimates came after a morethorough analysis of the available options and anunderstanding of regulatory requirements. The company expectsto meet the requirements through improved technology andswitching of fuels. The primary smokestack emissions aresulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxide.</TEXT></DOC>